revision.text:
{{Orphan|date=November 2016}}
'''Ann J. Lane''' (1931–2013) was an American educator, historian, and author that was considered to be a pioneer in the fields of [[women’s history]] and [[women’s studies]].<ref name=OAH>{{cite web|title=In Memorian, Ann J. Lane|url=http://www.oah.org/pages/ann-lane/|publisher=[[Organization of American Historians]]|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> Before retiring in 2009 she worked at the [[University of Virginia]] as a professor of History and director of Women’s Studies.<ref name=OAH />
Lane was born in Brooklyn and attended [[Brooklyn College]], where she graduated with a BA in English in 1952.<ref name=JWA>{{cite web|title=ANNJ.LANE|url=http://jwa.org/weremember/lane-ann|publisher=JWA|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> She went on to receive an MA in sociology from [[New York University]] and a PhD in American History from [[Columbia University]].
==Bibliography== *''The Debate over Slavery: Stanley Elkins and His Critics'' (1971) *''The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction'' (1971)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thornbrough|first1=Emma Lou|title=Reviewed Work: The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction by Ann J. Lane|journal=The Journal of American History|date=1972|volume=59|issue=1|pages=183–184|jstor=1888454}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Southern|first1=David W.|title=Reviewed Work: The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction by Ann J. Lane|journal=The Journal of Southern History|date=1972|volume=38|issue=3|pages=494–495|doi=10.2307/2206121|jstor=2206121}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gould|first1=Lewis L.|title=Reviewed Work: The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction by Ann J. Lane|journal=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly|date=1972|volume=75|issue=3|pages=395–396|jstor=30238159}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gatewood Jr.|first1=Willard B.|title=Reviewed Work: The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction by Ann J. Lane|journal=The Arkansas Historical Quarterly|date=1972|volume=31|issue=1|pages=82–86|doi=10.2307/40018549|jstor=40018549}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fletcher|first1=Marvin E.|title=Reviewed Work: The Brownsville Affair: National Crisis and Black Reaction. by Ann J. Lane|journal=Military Affairs|date=1972|volume=36|issue=3|page=111|doi=10.2307/1985325|jstor=1985325}}</ref> *''To "Herland" and Beyond: The Life and Work of Charlotte Perkins Gilman'' (1990)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kessler|first1=Carol Farley|title=Reviewed Works: To "Herland" and Beyond: The Life and Works of Charlotte Perkins Gilman by Ann J. Lane; Charlotte Perkins Gilman: The Woman and Her Work by Sheryl L. Meyerling|journal=Utopian Studies|date=1990|volume=1|issue=2|pages=158–161|jstor=20719010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fishbein|first1=Leslie|title=Reviewed Work: To Herland and Beyond: The Life and Work of Charlotte Perkins Gilman. by Ann J. Lane|journal=The Journal of American History|date=1993|volume=80|issue=3|page=1116|doi=10.2307/2080507|jstor=2080507}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Biamonte|first1=Gloria A.|title=Reviewed Work: To "Herland" and Beyond: The Life and Work of Charlotte Perkins Gilman by Ann J. Lane|journal=Legacy|date=1992|volume=9|issue=2|pages=155–157|jstor=25684465}}</ref>
