'''Lyster Hoxie Dewey''' (1865–1944) was an [[United States|American]] [[botany|botanist]] from [[Michigan]].
He was born in [[Cambridge Township, Michigan|Cambridge]], Michigan.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/12/AR2010051204933.html WashingtonPost.com: "Hemp fans look toward Lyster Dewey's past, and the Pentagon, for higher ground"], by Manuel Roig-Franzia, 13 May 2010 . accessed 04.22.2017.</ref> In 1888, he graduated from [[Michigan State University|Michigan Agricultural College]] where, for the next two years, he taught botany.
==Career== Dewey was an assistant botanist of the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] from 1890 to 1902, and thereafter botanist in charge of [[fiber]] investigations and [[fiber plant]]s research.
In 1911, he was the U.S. representative to the International Fibre Congress, held in [[Surabaya]] on [[Java]] island, in the [[Dutch East Indies]] (present day Indonesia).
===Publications=== His publications comprised bulletins of the United States Department of Agriculture, on:<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/fiberproductioni518dewe#page/66/mode/2up Lyster Hoxie Dewey: Fiber production in the western hemisphere, United states printing office, Washington, 1943]</ref> * the production of fiber from [[flax]], [[hemp]] (''[[Cannabis]]'' species), [[sisal]], and [[manila (fiber)|manila]] plants * the origin of [[cotton]] and classification of the varieties of [[Gossypium|cotton plants (''Gossypium'' species)]]. * investigations on [[Poacea|grasses]] and invasive troublesome [[weed]]s.
He wrote about growing exotically named varieties of [[hemp]] on USDA research land in Virginia known as the [[Arlington Farms|Arlington Experimental Farm]], site of the present day [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]].
===Taxonomist abbreviation=== {{botanist|L.H.Dewey|Dewey, Lyster Hoxie}}
