[[File:Pete3 copy.jpg|thumbnail|Pete DePoe]] {{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox musical artist |name=Peter DePoe |alias = Last Walking Bear |birth_name= |background = non_vocal_instrumentalist |associated_acts=[[Redbone (band)|Redbone]] |birth_date={{birth year and age|1943}} |birth_place=[[Neah Bay, Washington]], United States |death_date= |death_place= |genre=[[Rock music|Rock]], [[Pop music|pop]] |occupation=Musician, drummer |instruments=Drums }}
'''Peter DePoe''' (also known as '''Last Walking Bear''') is a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] [[Rock music|rock]] musician who is perhaps best-known as the drummer for the Native American band [[Redbone (band)|Redbone]]. Born in [[Neah Bay, Washington]] in 1943, his tribal Ancestors are [[Chief White Antelope Cheyenne people|Southern Cheyenne]], [[]], [[Turtle Mountain Chippewa]], [[Chief Charlie DePoe Cha' May Ton|Rogue River/Siletz ]]. DePoe is also of French and German descent. He first played with Jimi Hendrix in the Seattle area local taverns as a young man and then moved to California and became Redbone's drummer in 1969. He was credited with developing a style of drumming known as "King Kong". In early 1972, he left the group. The band replaced him with Arturo Perez, and then with Redbone bandmate [[Tony Bellamy]]'s [[Filipino people|Filipino]]-[[Mexican American]], Butch Rillera.<ref name="NamaHonor">[http://www.nativeamericanmusicawards.com/newsremembrance.cfm Native American Music Awards – "In Their Honor"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412000412/http://www.nativeamericanmusicawards.com/newsremembrance.cfm |date=April 12, 2010 }}</ref>
